stories: Bias triangles in stability diagrams of quantum dot devices symbolize important features, which are key indicators for examining spin physics. Nevertheless, barriers related to data quality and availability, as well as the intricacies of physical phenomena under study, have obstructed the development of an automatic and bespoke analytical framework, frequently relying on human analysis and verification. We present a new feature extraction method for bias triangles based on unsupervised, segmentation-based computer vision techniques. This method enables the direct detection and quantification of physical properties, thereby eliminating the need for human input or large training datasets, and enables the automation of pixel-level shape and feature labeling. Specifically, our approach allows for effective, efficient, and training-data-free detection of Pauli spin blockade phenomenon.
